{  
"response_text": "The mean household risk attitude tracks the average deviation of extension agents (E-RO, E-LBD, E-RO-SL1) from the recommended herd size over 100 years. Initially, all agents start at risk-attitude values near 0.5, reflecting baseline risk tolerance. By step 30, a sharp divergence emerges due to rainfall shocks (rain-std=100). E-RO agents (fixed rules) show minimal deviation, maintaining stable risk attitudes between 0.4 and 0.6. E-LBD agents, sensitive to personal outcomes, gradually increase risk-seeking behavior (values rising to ~0.7 post-step 40) as herd reductions fail to mitigate pasture stress from high livestock-init=90. E-RO-SL1 agents display erratic trends, with risk attitudes oscillating between 0.2 and 0.8 depending on neighbors\u2019 strategies within knowledge-radius=1. Post-step 60, rainfall variability induces recurring troughs across all agent types, though E-RO-SL1 groups synchronize risk adjustments earlier (step 80). By step 100, E-LBD converges to risk-attitudes ~0.3\u20130.4, prioritizing adaptive conservatism, while E-RO-SL1 populations stabilize near 0.4\u20130.6, contingent on localized knowledge replication. The absence of resting mechanisms (resting?=False) exacerbates deviation magnitudes, particularly in E-LBD, as pasture productivity lags recovery (gr1=0.5, gr2=0.1). Climate shocks amplify divergence between agent types, while social learning mediates stability in E-RO-SL1 groups."  
}

